7 An Act relating to professions and occupations;
amending Section 3, Chapter 291, O.S.L. 2024 (59 O.S.
8 Supp. 2024, Section 538.3), which relates to laser
hair removal practitioners; authorizing certain
9 professionals to perform laser hair removal;
requiring oversight of laser hair removal facilities
10 by certain professionals; requiring the establishment
of patient relationships; providing for the creation
11 of patient charts; deleting evaluation or referral
exception; and declaring an emergency.
12
13
14 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
15 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY Section 3, Chapter 291, O.S.L.
16 2024 (59 O.S. Supp. 2024, Section 538.3), is amended to read as
17 follows:
18 Section 538.3. A. A laser practitioner shall only perform
19 laser hair removal using lasers or pulsed light devices approved by
20 the United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for noninvasive
21 procedures.
22 B. A person shall not perform or attempt to perform laser hair
23 removal unless the person holds the appropriate health professional
24 license or certificate as defined in Section 2 538.2 of this act
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1658 Page 1

1 titl e, or the person is a laser practitioner performing laser hair
2 removal under the supervision of a physician as defined in
3 paragraphs 1 through 6 of subsection A of Section 725.2 of this
4 title, a certified physician assistant, or a certified Advanced
5 Practice Registered Nurse. A laser practitioner who is not a
6 physician shall complete a laser practitioner training and education
7 program. A laser training and education program may be completed
8 internally at the laser hair removal facility or via a third party,
9 provided such third-party program is overseen by a physician. A
10 laser practitioner training and education program shall include
11 forty (40) total hours of training, which may be a combination of
12 didactic training, in-person hands-on training, and performance of
13 laser hair removal procedures.
14 C. A laser hair removal facility shall be overseen by a
15 physician; provided, that Advanced Practice Registered Nurses shall
16 be exempt from this oversight requirement, as defined in paragraphs
17 1 through 6 of subsection A of Section 725.2 of this title, a
18 certified physician assistant, or a certified Advanced Practice
19 Registered Nurse.
20 D. The overseeing physician shall:
21 1. Establish proper protocols for laser hair removal provided
22 at a facility including, but not limited to, complication
23 management. A laser practitioner shall follow all written procedure
24 protocols established and revised by the overseeing physician. Such
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1658 Page 2

1 prot ocols shall require utilizing a physician, physician assistant,
2 or Advanced Practice Registered Nurse for complication management;
3 2. Determine the number of laser practitioners under such
4 physician's supervision; and
5 3. Review not less than ten percent (10%) of laser hair removal
6 patient records.
7 Every physician or physician assistant or Advanced Practice
8 Registered Nurse shall establish a relationship with patients which
9 shall include an initial evaluation, prior to treatment, that is
10 either face-to-face or via telemedicine that is performed by the
11 physician or physician assistant or Advanced Practice Registered
12 Nurse.
13 As part of the patient relationship, each physician or certified
14 physician assistant or certified Advanced Practice Registered Nurse
15 shall create a patient chart. The chart shall contain an informed
16 consent, a treatment plan that includes risks, benefits,
17 alternatives, follow-up, and care for potential complications.
18 E. A physician shall not be required to be physically present
19 or to supervise laser hair removal, but shall be available for
20 communication during the procedure, either in person or by two-way,
21 real time interactive communication.
22 F. A laser practitioner may perform laser hair removal on a
23 patient without the prior evaluation or referral of such patient by
24 a physician.
